	"conclusion": "For Notion, the career page partially precedes Linkedin: 22% of matched jobs (10/45) appeared on the career page first, with an average lead of 119 days (median: 43 days). An additional 106 jobs (70% of career-page listings) were never indexed by Linkedin at all. This confirms that the career page is the primary source of truth for job postings.",
	"geminiSummary": "Analysis of recent job posting data indicates that while company career pages do, in some instances, publish job opportunities before LinkedIn, the advantage is not universal and can vary significantly. Of the 45 unique job postings successfully matched across both platforms within the analysis period (2024-01-01 to 2026-04-01), only 10 (22%) appeared first on the company's career page. For these specific roles, the career page offered a substantial lead, with an average advantage of 119 days and a median advantage of 43 days. Moreover, a significant number of jobs, 106, were found exclusively on career pages and never observed on LinkedIn during the study, suggesting a broader advantage for direct company site monitoring.\n\nDelving into the lag distribution for jobs appearing first on career pages reveals a varied landscape for job seekers. While some opportunities provide a quick head start (2 jobs within 1-3 days), many offer a more substantial, albeit less consistent, lead. Two jobs were observed with a 15-30 day lead, another two within 31-60 days, one within 61-90 days, and a notable three jobs demonstrated a lag exceeding 90 days. This uneven distribution, ranging from a few days to over 600 days as seen in some top evidence cases, indicates that while a significant lead is possible, the precise timing advantage is unpredictable and not uniformly short, with the median suggesting a multi-week head start.\n\nIt is important to acknowledge certain caveats that may influence these findings. The disparity in snapshot frequency—200 career page snapshots versus only 6 LinkedIn snapshots—means that LinkedIn's job posting dates might be underestimated or jobs could have appeared and disappeared between snapshots, potentially skewing the \"LinkedIn first\" count or the measured lag. Furthermore, the extensive number of \"career page only\" jobs could be partly due to the limited LinkedIn crawl coverage or the specific sampling dates, rather than a definitive absence of those jobs on LinkedIn at any point. These limitations highlight the challenge of comprehensive tracking across dynamic online platforms.\n\nFor job seekers, these findings offer a clear practical recommendation: consistently monitoring company career pages directly, in addition to using platforms like LinkedIn, can provide a distinct competitive advantage. While LinkedIn remains a crucial resource, actively checking target companies' career sites offers the potential to discover roles weeks, or even months, before they gain broader visibility on professional networking sites. This proactive approach could be particularly beneficial for roles with longer application windows or those that are less frequently syndicated, increasing the likelihood of being among the first applicants.",
